---

---

<section class="py-28 md:py-36 px-6 md:px-16">
  <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto">
    <div
      class="flex flex-col md:flex-row justify-between items-start md:items-end gap-6 mb-20"
    >
      <div>
        <h2
          class="font-headline text-basalt text-4xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl leading-[1.02] max-w-3xl tracking-tight"
        >
          Four <em class="italic text-ochre">ways in</em>.
        </h2>
      </div>
      <p
        class="font-body text-basalt/70 max-w-md text-[15px] leading-relaxed"
      >
        Every visitor finds a different island. Some come for the ruins. Some
        for the reef. Some to walk a ridge their grandfather walked. Here are
        four places to start.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div
      class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-4 gap-10 lg:gap-8"
    >
      <!-- Chapter I — Nan Madol -->
      <a
        href="/nan-madol"
        class="reveal chapter flex flex-col gap-5 group mt-0"
      >
        <div class="relative aspect-[3/4] overflow-hidden bg-sand-deep">
          <img
            class="w-full h-full object-cover transition-transform duration-700 ease-[cubic-bezier(0.16,1,0.3,1)] group-hover:scale-[1.06]"
            src="https://res.cloudinary.com/doruy2kdr/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto,c_fill,g_auto,w_900,h_1200/chapter-01-nan-madol.jpg"
            alt="Nan Madol basalt ruins — A Lost City in the Sea"
            loading="lazy"
          />
          <div
            class="absolute top-0 left-0 w-10 h-10 bg-ochre text-sand font-headline italic text-lg flex items-center justify-center"
          >
            I
          </div>
          <div class="absolute bottom-0 left-0 w-full h-2 tapa-divider"></div>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-headline text-2xl leading-tight">
            Nan <em class="italic text-ochre">Madol</em>
          </h3>
          <p
            class="font-body text-[13px] text-basalt/60 mt-2 uppercase tracking-[0.15em]"
          >
            A Lost City in the Sea
          </p>
          <p class="font-body text-sm text-basalt/75 mt-3 leading-relaxed">
            Built between the 12th and 17th centuries by the Saudeleur Dynasty —
            massive basalt logs and coral fill on artificial islets connected by
            tidal canals. A UNESCO World Heritage Site, sometimes called the
            Venice of the Pacific — but there's nothing else like it.
          </p>
        </div>
      </a>

      <!-- Chapter II — Waterfalls & Jungle -->
      <a
        href="#adventures"
        id="adventures"
        class="reveal chapter flex flex-col gap-5 group md:mt-20"
        style="transition-delay: 0.12s;"
      >
        <div class="relative aspect-[3/4] overflow-hidden bg-sand-deep">
          <img
            class="w-full h-full object-cover transition-transform duration-700 ease-[cubic-bezier(0.16,1,0.3,1)] group-hover:scale-[1.06]"
            src="https://res.cloudinary.com/doruy2kdr/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto,c_fill,g_auto,w_900,h_1200/chapter-02-wild-interior.jpg"
            alt="Pohnpei waterfalls and jungle trails"
            loading="lazy"
          />
          <div
            class="absolute top-0 left-0 w-10 h-10 bg-ochre text-sand font-headline italic text-lg flex items-center justify-center"
          >
            II
          </div>
          <div class="absolute bottom-0 left-0 w-full h-2 tapa-divider"></div>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-headline text-2xl leading-tight">
            Waterfalls & <em class="italic text-ochre">Jungle</em>
          </h3>
          <p
            class="font-body text-[13px] text-basalt/60 mt-2 uppercase tracking-[0.15em]"
          >
            40 Waterfalls · Sokehs Ridge · Rainforest Trails
          </p>
          <p class="font-body text-sm text-basalt/75 mt-3 leading-relaxed">
            Pohnpei gets 300+ inches of rain a year. That water has to go
            somewhere — it runs through volcanic highlands as rivers, pools,
            and more than 40 waterfalls. The trail to Sokehs Ridge starts steep
            and doesn't stop. WWII fortifications hide in the jungle alongside
            views of the entire island.
          </p>
        </div>
      </a>

      <!-- Chapter III — Diving & Surfing -->
      <a
        href="/diving-and-surfing"
        id="diving-surfing"
        class="reveal chapter flex flex-col gap-5 group mt-0"
        style="transition-delay: 0.24s;"
      >
        <div class="relative aspect-[3/4] overflow-hidden bg-sand-deep">
          <img
            class="w-full h-full object-cover transition-transform duration-700 ease-[cubic-bezier(0.16,1,0.3,1)] group-hover:scale-[1.06]"
            src="https://res.cloudinary.com/doruy2kdr/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto,c_fill,g_auto,w_900,h_1200/chapter-03-diving-surfing.jpg"
            alt="Diving and surfing at Palikir Pass, Pohnpei"
            loading="lazy"
          />
          <div
            class="absolute top-0 left-0 w-10 h-10 bg-ochre text-sand font-headline italic text-lg flex items-center justify-center"
          >
            III
          </div>
          <div class="absolute bottom-0 left-0 w-full h-2 tapa-divider"></div>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-headline text-2xl leading-tight">
            Diving & <em class="italic text-ochre">Surfing</em>
          </h3>
          <p
            class="font-body text-[13px] text-basalt/60 mt-2 uppercase tracking-[0.15em]"
          >
            Palikir Pass · Manta Road · Reef Walls
          </p>
          <p class="font-body text-sm text-basalt/75 mt-3 leading-relaxed">
            Pohnpei is a name surfers know. Palikir Pass and P-Pass pull in
            pilgrims chasing glass. Below the surface, the barrier reef opens
            into manta corridors, coral walls, and WWII wrecks. The water is
            warm year-round. The reef is always accessible.
          </p>
        </div>
      </a>

      <!-- Chapter IV — Living Culture -->
      <a
        href="#culture"
        id="culture"
        class="reveal chapter flex flex-col gap-5 group md:mt-20"
        style="transition-delay: 0.36s;"
      >
        <div class="relative aspect-[3/4] overflow-hidden bg-sand-deep">
          <img
            class="w-full h-full object-cover transition-transform duration-700 ease-[cubic-bezier(0.16,1,0.3,1)] group-hover:scale-[1.06]"
            src="https://res.cloudinary.com/doruy2kdr/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto,c_fill,g_auto,w_900,h_1200/chapter-04-living-culture.jpg"
            alt="Pohnpeian living culture"
            loading="lazy"
          />
          <div
            class="absolute top-0 left-0 w-10 h-10 bg-ochre text-sand font-headline italic text-lg flex items-center justify-center"
          >
            IV
          </div>
          <div class="absolute bottom-0 left-0 w-full h-2 tapa-divider"></div>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-headline text-2xl leading-tight">
            Living <em class="italic text-ochre">Culture</em>
          </h3>
          <p
            class="font-body text-[13px] text-basalt/60 mt-2 uppercase tracking-[0.15em]"
          >
            Tiahk · Sakau · The Nahnmwarki
          </p>
          <p class="font-body text-sm text-basalt/75 mt-3 leading-relaxed">
            Pohnpei's culture isn't behind glass. The chieftainship system is
            active. Sakau is pounded and shared every evening. First-harvest
            feasts still mark the seasons. If you're here, you're welcome to
            witness it.
          </p>
        </div>
      </a>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
